-Kalpana Chawla was an Indian-American astronaut who made history as the first woman of Indian origin in space. Born in Karnal, India, she earned a degree in aeronautical engineering before joining NASA.

-Aryabhatta was an ancient Indian mathematician and astronomer who made significant contributions to trigonometry, algebra, and astronomy, including the concept of zero, the decimal system, and the approximation of the value of pi.

-Srinivasa Ramanujan was an great Indian mathematician who made profound contributions to mathematical analysis, number theory, infinite series, and continued fractions. His remarkable talent and insights earned him recognition as one of the most brilliant mathematical minds in history.

-DR. APJ Abdul Kalam widely known as the "Missile Man of India," was a distinguished scientist, educator, and the 11th President of India. Renowned for his pivotal role in India's space and missile development programs, he played a crucial part in the country's technological advancements.
